 for the First Crusade":"Northamptonshire, Anglie","Bretagne, France":"Bretagne, Francie","Palestine":"Palestina"},"da":{"about 1011–21 December 1096":"omkring 1011–21. december 1096","1011–1096":"1011–1096","1059–1096":"1059–1096","1026–1099":"1026–1099","1039–1096":"1039–1096","1073–Male":"1073–Afdød","1096–Male":"1096–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","about 1096":"omkring 1096","1039":"1039","21 December 1096":"21. december 1096","1026":"1026","1059":"1059","about 1039":"omkring 1039","1099":"1099","1011":"1011","before 1096":"før 1096","1096":"1096","1073":"1073","about 1011":"omkring 1011","Gaël, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Angevin Empire":"Gaël, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Frankrig","Brittany, France":"Bretagne, Frankrig","On the way to Palestine for the First Crusade":"Northamptonshire, England","Bretagne, France":"Bretagne, Frankrig","Palestine":"Palæstina"},"nl":{"about 1011–21 December 1096":"circa 1011–21 december 1096","1011–1096":"1011–1096","1059–1096":"1059–1096","1026–1099":"1026–1099","1039–1096":"1039–1096","1073–Male":"1073–Overleden","1096–Male":"1096–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","about 1096":"circa 1096","1039":"1039","21 December 1096":"21 december 1096","1026":"1026","1059":"1059","about 1039":"circa 1039","1099":"1099","1011":"1011","before 1096":"vóór 1096","1096":"1096","1073":"1073","about 1011":"circa 1011","Gaël, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Angevin Empire":"Gaël, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Frankrijk","Brittany, France":"Bretagne, Frankrijk","On the way to Palestine for the First Crusade":"Northamptonshire, England","Bretagne, France":"Bretagne, Frankrijk","Palestine":"Palestina"},"en":{"about 1011–21 December 1096":"about 1011–21 December 1096","1011–1096":"1011–1096","1059–1096":"1059–1096","1026–1099":"1026–1099","1039–1096":"1039–1096","1073–Male":"1073–Deceased","1096–Male":"1096–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","about 1096":"about 1096","1039":"1039","21 December 1096":"21 December 1096","1026":"1026","1059":"1059","about 1039":"about 1039","1099":"1099","1011":"1011","before 1096":"before 1096","1096":"1096","1073":"1073","about 1011":"about 1011","Gaël, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Angevin Empire":"Gaël, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France","Brittany, France":"Brittany, France","On the way to Palestine for the First Crusade":"Northamptonshire, England","Bretagne, France":"Brittany, France","Palestine":"Palestine","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gael","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish, Welsh, and Irish: nickname from Celtic <i>gall</i> ‘foreigner, stranger’, a word found in Irish, Gaelic, and Breton. In the Scottish Highlands the Gaelic term <i>gall</i> was applied to people from the English-speaking lowlands and to Scandinavians; in Ireland the same term was applied to settlers who arrived from Wales and England in the wake of the Anglo-Norman invasion of the 12th century. This surname is also found at an early date in Lincolnshire, where it apparently has a Breton origin (compare 4 below and   Legall  ), having been introduced by Breton followers of the Norman Conquerors.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Gale  .","French, German, Danish, Polish, and Czech; Slovak (mainly <b>Gáll</b>); Hungarian (<b>Gáll</b>): from the Latin personal name <i>Gallus</i>, originally a Roman surname meaning ‘Gaul’ or ‘rooster’ (see   Gallo   2). The name was widespread in Europe during the Middle Ages, in central Europe largelly due to the cult of a 7th-century Irish monk and missionary, Saint Gall, whose name, Latinized as <i>Gallus</i>, is presumably of Celtic origin (see 1 above). Among other things, Saint Gall established a Christian settlement to the south of Lake Constance, which became the monastery later known as St. Gallen. The Latin(ized) name <i>Gallus</i> was taken into Czech as   Havel  , into Polish as <i>Gaweł</i> (see   Gawel  ), into Slovak and Hungarian as <i>Gál</i> (see   Gal  ), and into Slovenian and Croatian as   Gal  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Galbraith","meanings":["Scottish: ethnic name for a Strathclyde Briton, from Gaelic <i>gall Breathnach</i> ‘British foreigner’. Compare   Gall  .","History: This name is first recorded as a surname in the Lennox, a rich agricultural region north of Glasgow under the Campsie Fells, in the 12th century. In early medieval times the region to which Lennox belongs was an independent Welsh-speaking kingdom, with its capital at Dumbarton. It was not integrated into the rest of Scotland until 1124. The first recorded chief of the Galbraiths was Gilchrist ‘the Briton’, living in 1193."]},{"name":"Gal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Aharon, Eti, Ofer, Aviva, Dorit, Dov, Gadi, Moshe, Noam, Ronen.  Hungarian Imre, Sandor, Janos, Laszlo, Bela, Ildiko.  Polish Andrej, Dariusz, Feliks, Kazimierz, Stanislaw, Wlodzimierz.","Hungarian, Slovak, and Czech (<b>Gál</b>); Polish (also <b>Gał</b>); Rusyn (in Slovakia also <b>Gál</b>, in Poland also <b>Gał</b>); Slovenian and Croatian: from the personal name Hungarian, Slovak, and Czech <i>Gál</i>, Polish, Rusyn, Slovenian, and Croatian <i>Gal</i>, from Latin <i>Gallus</i> (see   Gall   3), the name borne by a 7th-century Irish missionary who was very active in central Europe and is venerated as a saint in the Catholic Church. This personal name was widespread in Europe in the Middle Ages, and it gave rise to many surnames, e.g. Slovak <b>Galko</b>, <b>Galčík</b>,   Galik  ,   Gall  ,   Gallik  , <b>Galovič</b> (see   Galovic  ), and   Galus  , and Slovenian   Gale  . In North America, the surname <i>Gal</i> could also be a shortening of some of them.","Croatian and Slovenian: from the old personal name <i>Gal</i>, from <i>gal</i>, an obsolete word meaning ‘black’."]},{"name":"Gallman","meanings":["Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Gallmann</b>: variant of   Gall   3, with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Galler","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Fritz, Otto, Reinhold.  Jewish Hyman, Emanuel, Meyer, Myer, Naum.","German: patronymic from a personal name (from Latin <i>Gallus</i>) which was widespread in Europe in the Middle Ages (see   Gall   3).","German: nickname for someone in the service of the monastery of St. Gallen (see   Gall   3), or a habitational name for someone from the city in Switzerland so named."]},{"name":"Galiano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Blanca, Jaime, Jorge, Juan, Julio, Pedro.  Italian Dino, Eduardo, Rolando, Adolfo, Aida, Angelo, Fausto, Gennaro, Luciano, Nunzio, Rocco.","Spanish and southern Italian: from the personal name <i>Galiano</i>, from the Late Latin name <i>Gallianus</i>, a derivative of <i>Gallius</i>, from <i>Gallus</i> (see   Gall   3). Compare Italian   Galliano  .","Italian: habitational name from a place called Galiano."]},{"name":"Gallet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Alain, Gilberte, Michel, Pierre, Vernice, Yves.","French:","nickname for a cheerful companion, a noun derivative of the Old French verb <i>gal(l)er</i> ‘to enjoy oneself, to have fun’."]},{"name":"Legall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Yves, Aliette, Francois, Jean Luc, Michel, Mireille.","Breton (mainly Finistère and Côtes-d'Armor; mainly <b>Le Gall</b>): nickname for a French-speaking person in Brittany, from Breton <i>Gall</i> ‘Gaulish person, Frenchman’, with the French masculine definite article <i>le</i>. See also   Gall   4.","German: variant of   Legel   ‘cooper’ and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Galle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Amie, Colette, Yves.","German: variant of   Gall  , or a nickname for an evil person, from Middle High German <i>galle</i> ‘bile, bitterness, falsehood’.","Flemish: from the personal name <i>Galle</i>, a Romance or French form of ancient Germanic <i>Wal(l)o</i> ‘man from Wallonia’."]},{"name":"Galliano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Dante, Enrico, Geno.  French Alain, Monique.","Italian (mainly Piedmont): from the personal name <i>Galliano</i>, from the Late Latin name <i>Gallianus</i>, a derivative of <i>Gallius</i>, from <i>Gallus</i> (see   Gall   3). This surname is also found in southern France. Compare   Galiano  ."]},{"name":"Galewski","meanings":["Polish: habitational name for someone from Galew, two villages in Greater Poland Voivodeship, or Galewice in Łódź Voivodeship. See also   Gall   3."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Ralph de Gael The Staller Earl of Suffolk and Norfolk was born about 1011, in Brittany, France as the son of Earl Ralph. He had at least 1 son with Gytha Countess of Hereford. He died on 21 December 1096, at the age of 86."},"et":{"about 1011–21 December 1096":"umbes 1011–21. detsember 1096","1011–1096":"1011–1096","1059–1096":"1059–1096","1026–1099":"1026–1099","1039–1096":"1039–1096","1073–Male":"1073–Surnud","1096–Male":"1096–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","about 1096":"umbes 1096","1039":"1039","21 December 1096":"21. detsember 1096","1026":"1026","1059":"1059","about 1039